column30: The louder the noise, the more I associated with the higher alcohol percentage.
I picked the louder one for more alcohol
So I'm guessing the alcohol contain yeast, and it produces carbon dioxide which create the sound. So the deeper? the sound is the more alcohol it contain? I don't know man I just I guess.
I mostly guessed, but for both sets of sounds I associated the one that, to me, sounded a bit stronger/more forceful with the higher alcohol content.
the sounds i picked seemed a lil more unplesant, so assumed it was the stronger liqour causing it. other then that no clue.
picked the one that sounded more dramatic
I think I somehow was making a connection between volume of the sound and strength, I'm not really sure I just went with my first impression after one time of listening to the clips.
One of the sounds seemed more open and relaxed to me, and that's the one I picked for the 30% liquor.
I associated the harsher sound with the higher tax.
I picked the sound that sounded harsher as the one with a higher alcohol content.
The longer sound seemed as if someone was reacting more to the higher alcohol.  Or what the sound I assume they would make.
I tried to go more for the sound that sounded "heavier" or "more emphasized" to represent a higher alcohol content.
the louder as being the 30% no other reason
I for some reason believe a drink with a higher alcohol content would have a lighter-duller sound.
The lower pitched one is the one I think I selected, because it makes me think of a stronger reaction, like to higher alcohol content.
I thought one was a little more startled sounding.
The sounds I picked sounded more intense and pronounced to my ear.
I would assume the 30% alcohol might burn more going down one's throat and I thought the second files in both questions correlated with this assumption.
30% is stronger so stronger sounding file is the one I chose. and in both cases, the second sounded stronger.
I picked the sound that sounded more jarring or distinct to me because I think a 30% liquor would be much more jarring to drink in terms of overall effect on the body.
I feel like I associated the 'stronger' sounding noise to the 30% alcohol since it was the stronger of two drinks.
I thought a longer and deeper sound would fit rice liquor better.
I chose the sound with the highest pitch for the 30% and the lower for 15%
I tried to imagine the person who seemed more intoxicated and pictured her making the sound.
I went for what sound was stronger/more prominent for the higher percentage
While listening to the sounds, I remembered how I felt the first time I tasted sake many years ago and how it just threw me back because I was totally unprepared for the taste and temperature.
I felt the more harsh sounds would match the 30% alcohol, because people would perceive the kick to be stronger even if the tastes were the same.

I'm trying to figure out why I picked the second sound to represent the higher alcohol content. I guess the second sound seemed almost like a long sigh. People usually take a long sigh after tasting strong alcohol. I hope that made sense.
The heavier sound for 30%
I chose at random
I felt like the 30 percent alcohol one would have a deeper sound than the 15 percent one so i chose the one that sounded more powerful in my opinion
The ones that sound more bubbly or carbonated I associated with the 30%. I don't have any particular rationale besides that.
The harsher sounds or lower sounds seemed to remind me of an unpleasant sound which made me think it had more alcohol in it.
I chose the shorter and sharper sound for the 30% alcohol content because it sounds more "wow that was strong"
There is some difference in the vocal sound. Based on that I have selected the options.
I thought that the one that was deeper and less high pitched might be the 30% but I don't know why I decided that.
I associated the lower pitched and slightly louder sound with higher alcohol content.  I don't know if that is correct or not, but it is my first instinct for the sounds.
I felt like the longer noises helped to determine 30%.
I guess just by how bold and long the first sound was.
For the first trial I chose the sound that was higher pitched and for the 2nd trial I chose the sound that I felt was a longer puff of air.

The first sound clip sounded more concentrated while the second one seemed to evaporate in a sense. For this reason, I decided to associate the first sound clip with the 30% alcohol, the more concentrated alcohol content.
The second one sounded like it had more fizz to it
The deeper voice makes me think more alcohol.
Stronger/louder sounds, sounding more satisfied but also a little more startled (while I know the taste is identical, stronger liquor often has a bit more bite)
I don't know. I just went with a gut feeling. The sounds were kind of weird and creepy to begin with.
the 30% should be a louder, sharper sound.
The sounds I selected were closer to the sounds of (pain) in my opinion than refreshment.

To me the sound that seemed to have a "c" noise would take more effort and one would need to have a good reason to put that much work into showing disguist or displeasure. Though I will say it was hard not to choose the first choices because they seemed more fluid.
The loudest sound seems to reflect a stronger alcohol content. If a person sips a beer, there is no sound, if you have a shot of moonshine, you are a lot louder!
I felt the 30% liqueur would have a stronger, louder response associated with it, hence why I chose the way that I did.
The louder the sound, the more likely I thought it had the higher alcohol content.
I figured that 15% would be considered lighter than 30%, so I chose the sounds that I perceived as heavier, deeper, more dense. Anything lighter, higher pitch I associated with the 15%.
I thought the 30% liquor would have a higher pitch
The stronger physical response sound made me think of the stronger alcohol content.
